me from any of numerous places called Houghton or Hoghton. Most of the placenames derive from Old English <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some have different etymologies; for example, Little Houghton in Eccles (Lancashire), which derives from Old English <i>halh</i> ‘nook, corner of land’ + <i>tūn</i>, and Houghton in Bigbury (Devon), which may derive from an Old English personal name <i>Huhha</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i>.","variant of   Haughton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Haughton","meanings":["English: habitational name from Haughton (Cheshire, Lancashire, Northumberland, Shropshire, Staffordshire), or Haughton le Skerne (Durham). The placenames derive from Old English <i>halh</i> ‘nook, corner of land’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Houghton  .","Irish: adopted for <b>Ó hEacháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eachán</i>’, a pet form of the personal name <i>Eachaidh</i> (see   Hoey  ).","Irish: adopted for <b>Ó hEachtair</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eachtair</i>’, a personal name of uncertain origin. Compare   Hoctor  ."]},{"name":"Howton","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Houghton  ."]},{"name":"Hufton","meanings":["English: habitational name; probably from Stony Houghton in Pleasley (Derbyshire), the name of which derives from Old English <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Houghton  ."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Emma Houghton was born in 1131, in England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Payne de Houghton, was 27 and her mother, Adeliza Raimes, was 31. She had at least 3 sons with Arnold Bois V. She died about 1194, in Thorpe Arnold, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1131–Abt 1194":"1131–umbes 1194","1131–1194":"1131–1194","1133–Female":"1133–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1159–1221":"1159–1221","1190–1255":"1190–1255","1192–Male":"1192–Surnud","1194–1225":"1194–1225","1105–1162":"1105–1162","1100–1162":"1100–1162","1190":"1190","about 1162":"umbes 1162","1131":"1131","1162":"1162","1194":"1194","1192":"1192","1105":"1105","Abt 1194":"umbes 1194","1225":"1225","1159":"1159","1255":"1255","1100":"1100","1221":"1221","1133":"1133","Thorpe Arnold, Leicestershire, England":"Thorpe Arnold, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Thorpe Arnold, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Thorpe Arnold, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1131–Abt 1194":"1131–noin 1194","1131–1194":"1131–1194","1133–Female":"1133–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1159–1221":"1159–1221","1190–1255":"1190–1255","1192–Male":"1192–Kuollut","1194–1225":"1194–1225","1105–1162":"1105–1162","1100–1162":"1100–1162","1190":"1190","about 1162":"noin 1162","1131":"1131","1162":"1162","1194":"1194","1192":"1192","1105":"1105","Abt 1194":"noin 1194","1225":"1225","1159":"1159","1255":"1255","1100":"1100","1221":"1221","1133":"1133","Thorpe Arnold, Leicestershire, England":"Thorpe Arnold, Leicestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Thorpe Arnold, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Thorpe Arnold, Leicestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1131–Abt 1194":"1131–environ 1194","1131–1194":"1131–1194","1133–Female":"1133–Décédée","–Female